<p>In a White House meeting on Friday, President Trump signaled reluctance to provide Ukraine with long-range Tomahawk cruise missiles, citing escalation risks and concerns about U.S. stockpiles, while saying he hopes to end the war without them [nytimes.com#1][time.com#1][euronews.com#2]. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky pressed his case and floated a drones‑for‑Tomahawks swap, arguing long-range strikes are needed to pressure Russia into serious talks [theglobeandmail.com#1][time.com#1]. After the meeting, Trump publicly urged Kyiv and Moscow to “stop where they are,” even suggesting both sides could “declare victory” and make a deal [npr.org#1][cbsnews.com#1]. The stance follows a two‑hour Thursday call with Vladimir Putin, after which Trump said he and the Russian leader would meet in Budapest within roughly two weeks; Zelensky countered that Putin is “not ready” for peace [theweek.com#1][dawn.com#1].</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/pGpSLKKU2_F7u9GWi3-C9AF8J4QtfbUUBXJKUqRQM26ksZfNiaji1W_Y7K1AMotFOzqow6lrTrasPlxV9Gq8WqznbdPnFc2QAY-SeKCBL4_y5vGRgntFKJqieq2XpNepTesGQOpks2EWxiVitwDyjw4QVDwZvjQKFQnwstUR5IOgHYMrzroKMOVjgMqorwHxTUukwhb05V3qRoe-GXJNyJkbOnwxTw6ce75bJ3HOT16cRgzkeRy6iwSVwnoGVB45MuRxoGL-eQJ1lNY1LQ' alt='President Trump greets President Zelensky outside the West Wing ahead of their meeting.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Drone proposal: Zelensky proposed trading thousands of Ukrainian-made drones and aiding U.S. drone supply in exchange for Tomahawks, a swap Trump said he would consider [abc.net.au#1][cbsnews.com#3][theglobeandmail.com#1].</li><li>Budapest groundwork: Trump said Secretary of State Marco Rubio will meet Russian Foreign Minister Sergey Lavrov as early as next week to prepare for a Budapest summit with Putin [theweek.com#1].</li><li>Zelensky’s expectations: After the talks, Zelensky described his chances of getting Tomahawks as “realistic,” noting U.S. reluctance reflected the position “for today” [politico.com#1][france24.com#2].</li><li>Putin’s warning: During their call, Putin cautioned Trump that delivering Tomahawks could escalate the war and jeopardize peace talks, according to accounts of the conversation [dawn.com#1].</li><li>Peace momentum: Trump highlighted his recent role in securing an Israel-Hamas ceasefire as he pushed diplomacy over additional long-range weapons for Ukraine [elpais.com#1][time.com#1].</li></ul><blockquote>We’d much rather not need Tomahawks. We’d much rather get the war over. - President Donald Trump</blockquote><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>President Trump: He prefers a ceasefire and warns that sending Tomahawks risks escalation while drawing down U.S. inventories, adding he believes Putin ultimately wants to end the war. (<a href='https://www.politico.com/news/2025/10/17/trump-still-convinced-putin-wants-to-end-this-war-lukewarm-on-zelenskyys-request-for-tomahawks-00613870'>Politico</a>)</li><li>Volodymyr Zelensky: He argues long‑range missiles are needed to force serious negotiations with Putin and offered a drones‑for‑missiles exchange, but acknowledged U.S. caution for now. (<a href='https://www.theglobeandmail.com/world/us-politics/article-ukraine-russia-trump-zelensky-meeting/'>The Globe and Mail</a>)</li><li>Kremlin: Moscow requested Thursday’s call and warned that a Tomahawk transfer would escalate the conflict and undermine peace prospects ahead of a planned Budapest summit. (<a href='https://www.dawn.com/news/1949567/trump-suggests-too-soon-for-tomahawks-in-talks-with-zelensky'>Dawn</a>)</li><li>Washington Post analysis: Analysts question whether Tomahawks would be a true battlefield &#x27;game changer&#x27; for Ukraine, noting their long-range strike role and launch platforms. (<a href='https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/2025/10/17/ukraine-tomahawk-russia-typhon-launcher/'>The Washington Post</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://english.elpais.com/usa/2025-10-17/trump-seeks-peace-in-ukraine-after-claiming-victo